{"cursor":"87381","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Stephen Sondheim image = Stephen Sondheim - smoking.JPG caption = c.\n| 1970 background = non_performing_personnel birth_name = Stephen Joshua\n| Sondheim birth_date = birth_place = New York City, New York, United States\n| genre = Musical theatre occupation = Composer, lyricist years_active =\n| 1954âpresent\n}} 'Stephen Joshua Sondheim' (; born March 22, 1930) is an American composer and\nlyricist known for his contributions to musical theatre. He is the winner of an\nAcademy Award, eight Tony Awards including the Special Tony Award for Lifetime\nAchievement in the\nTheatre, [http://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/archive/dyk/index.html \"Tony\nAwards Legacy Facts and Trivia\"] tonyawards.com. Retrieved March 14, 2010\nmultiple Grammy Awards, a Pulitzer Prize and the Laurence Olivier Award.\nDescribed by Frank Rich of the New York Times as \"now the greatest and perhaps\nbest-known artist in the American musical theater\", Rich, Frank.[http://www.nytimes.com/library/magazine/home/20000312mag-\nsondheim.html \"Conversations With Sondheim\"] The New York Times , March 12,\n2000, Magazine Section 6, p. 38 his most famous works include (as composer\nand lyricist) [[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]], [[Company\n(musical)|Company]], [[Follies]], [[A Little Night Music]], [[Sweeney Todd: The\nDemon Barber of Fleet Street (musical)|Sweeney Todd]], [[Sunday in the Park with\nGeorge]] and [[Into the Woods]]. He also wrote the lyrics for [[West Side\nStory]] and [[Gypsy: A Musical Fable|Gypsy]].\n\nSondheim has written material for movies, including the 1981 Warren Beatty film\n[[Reds (film)|Reds]], for which he contributed the song \"Goodbye For Now\". He\nalso wrote five songs for the 1990 movie [[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]],\nincluding \"Sooner or Later (I Always Get My Man)\" which won the Academy Award\nfor Best Song.\n\nHe was president of the Dramatists Guild from 1973 to 1981. In celebration of\nhis 80th birthday, the Henry Miller's Theatre was renamed the Stephen Sondheim\nTheatre on September 15, 2010, and the BBC Proms staged a concert in his honor.\nCameron Mackintosh has described Sondheim as \"possibly the greatest lyricist\never.\" Fanshawe,\nSimon.[http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2000/dec/09/books.guardianreview6 \"An\niconoclast on Broadway\"]The Guardian , December 12, 2000\n","linknr":1642,"url":"Stephen_Sondheim","recorded":1362477669,"links":61,"instances":["writer","magazine","actor","director","madonna_song","actress","booklet","entertainer","arlington_va","american_actor","musical"],"pdf":[],"categories":["American musical theatre composers","American musical theatre lyricists","Best Song Academy Award winning songwriters","Drama Desk Award winners","Edgar Award winners","Ethical Culture Fieldston School alumni","Grammy Award-winning artists","Jewish classical musicians","Jewish American composers and songwriters","Kennedy Center honorees","Laurence Olivier Award winners","LGBT musicians from the United States","LGBT composers","LGBT Jews","Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters","New York Military Academy alumni","People from New York City","Pulitzer Prize for Drama winners","Puzzle designers","Tony Award winners","United States National Medal of Arts recipients","Recipients of the Praemium Imperiale","Williams College alumni","1930 births","Living people","Honorary Members of the Royal Academy of Music","Gay musicians","Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences"],"headings":["Early years","Career","Major works","Minor works","Honors and awards","Legacy","Personal life","See also","Notes","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Stephen_Sondheim_-_smoking.JPG/220px-Stephen_Sondheim_-_smoking.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Symbol_book_class2.svg/16px-Symbol_book_class2.sv